## The Solitaire Standard: How Cut Quality Shows in a Solitaire

The Solitaire Standard is this: in a solitaire, the round brilliant's cut quality is the only variable that matters visually. Clarity, color, and carat weight affect the certificate — only cut quality affects what you see in the ring.

Here is what different GIA cut grades produce in a solitaire setting:

| GIA Cut Grade | What You See in a Solitaire | Farzana's Analytical Verdict |
|---|---|---|
| Excellent + ideal proportions (table 53–57%, depth 59–62%, PA 40.6–41°) | Maximum fire everywhere — rainbow flashes visible at any angle. Dead zones absent. Stone appears to generate its own light. | 10/10. The Solitaire Standard. This is the stone a solitaire was designed to show. Buy nothing below this for a pure solitaire. |
| Excellent (GIA grade, proportions at acceptable range edges) | High fire and brilliance. May have slight extinction zones at specific viewing angles. Still excellent performance. | 9/10. The Solid Choice. GIA Excellent with verified proportions (not just grade label) is the minimum for a solitaire. Verify the certificate numbers, not just the grade. |
| Very Good | Noticeably reduced fire and scintillation. Some extinction visible. In a solitaire, the contrast between VG and EX is immediately apparent. | 6/10. The Compromised Solitaire. In a halo, VG cut is acceptable — the melee compensates. In a solitaire, VG cut is visible to any observer. Do not buy a VG cut solitaire. |
| Good | Significant extinction zones. Stone appears flat or steely in normal lighting. Brilliance reduced. | 3/10. Never for a Solitaire. A Good cut stone in a solitaire is a disappointment. The setting exposes every performance deficiency. |

**The solitaire rule:** For any round brilliant in a solitaire, GIA Excellent cut is not a recommendation — it is the minimum requirement. The Solitaire Standard demands it.

