## Frequently Asked Questions

### What is a round diamond solitaire ring?
A round diamond solitaire ring is a single round brilliant cut diamond set in a plain or simple metal band with no additional stones. The setting holds the diamond with prongs (4 or 6), a bezel, or a tension mechanism. The solitaire format requires the diamond to perform entirely on its own — no halo, no melee, no setting details to supplement or mask the stone's light performance.

### How much does a round diamond solitaire ring cost in {{year}}?
A 1ct round brilliant GIA Excellent G-VS2 in a 14k white gold 4-prong solitaire starts at approximately $3,700–$4,000 total in {{month_year}}. In platinum, add $200–$500 for the setting upgrade. A 2ct round brilliant solitaire starts around $18,000 total with a platinum setting. Lab-grown solitaires — 1.5ct D-VVS1 IGI in platinum — total approximately $2,500–$3,500.

### What cut grade do I need for a round solitaire ring?
GIA Excellent cut is the minimum requirement for a round brilliant solitaire — not a preference, a requirement. In a solitaire, there are no surrounding elements to supplement light performance. A Very Good cut stone will show visible extinction zones that a halo would mask. Always verify the full GIA certificate: table 53–57%, depth 59–62.5%, pavilion angle 40.6–41°, culet None or Pointed.

### Is 4 prong or 6 prong better for a round diamond solitaire?
4-prong exposes more stone surface and creates a modern, clean aesthetic; 6-prong provides more security and is the classic design (the original Tiffany setting used 6 prongs). For active lifestyles, 6-prong platinum is the better choice. For lower-activity wear and a preference for a more contemporary look, 4-prong is excellent. Both are correct — the choice is lifestyle and aesthetic, not performance.

### What metal is best for a round diamond solitaire?
Platinum for G and H color diamonds in a solitaire — its permanently cool white color makes near-colorless stones appear fully colorless and requires no rhodium re-plating. 14k or 18k white gold is a cost-effective alternative that requires replating every 1–3 years. Yellow gold is excellent for I and J color diamonds where the warm metal tone complements the stone's slight warmth. Rose gold works with I–J color and adds a modern aesthetic.

### What color diamond should I buy for a solitaire ring?
G color is the sweet spot for a round brilliant solitaire in platinum or white gold — visually identical to D-F in a mounting, with meaningful savings. H color is excellent under 1.5ct in white gold. I and J color are acceptable in yellow gold where the warm metal masks body color. In a solitaire specifically, where the stone has no surrounding melee to dilute color, G is the recommended minimum in white metal.

### How do I choose between a natural and lab-grown diamond solitaire?
Natural solitaire: GIA-certified, 40–50% resale recovery, geological origin. The [1ct G-VS1 GIA at $3,300](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29161966?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) in platinum is the classic natural solitaire entry. Lab-grown solitaire: identical optical performance, 10–20% resale recovery, CVD or HPHT origin. The [1.5ct D-VVS1 IGI at $1,950](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29219792?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) in platinum delivers more visual presence than a natural 1ct for less total cost. The decision is about origin and resale, not appearance.

### What clarity do I need for a round diamond solitaire?
VS2 or VS1. Both are 100% eye-clean in round brilliants — the 57 facets mask peripheral inclusions completely. In a solitaire, no setting element assists the stone, but the round brilliant's own facet pattern does the work. VS2 at $3,230 is the rational starting point. Do not buy SI1 for a solitaire — the 30% risk of a visible inclusion is unacceptable in a setting with no masking elements.

### What is The Solitaire Standard?
The Solitaire Standard is my term for the requirement that a round brilliant solitaire demands: because the setting removes every visual crutch, the stone must perform entirely on cut quality alone. A well-cut GIA Excellent stone in a solitaire demonstrates peak light performance — fire, brilliance, and scintillation at every angle. A poorly cut stone in a solitaire cannot hide its deficiencies. The solitaire is the most demanding setting for cut quality because it is the most honest.

### Should I get a cathedral or low-profile solitaire setting?
Low-profile for active lifestyles; cathedral for formal or social-focused wear. Cathedral settings lift the stone higher and provide dramatic visual impact but increase snagging risk on clothing and catching on objects. Low-profile settings keep the stone close to the finger — more secure, less visually dominant. For everyday active wear, the low-profile 6-prong platinum solitaire is the superior practical choice.

